{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16677"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16677"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.26,0.02,0.64,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66279"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4188"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9331"},{"type":"tags","id":"11047"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66279"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing abdominal bloating, early satiety, and pelvic discomfort. She has lost 5 kg in weight over this period. She experienced menopause at age 52 and has no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a firm, non-tender mass in the left lower quadrant. Pelvic examination reveals a fixed 8 cm adnexal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECA-125: 450 U/mL (0-35)\u003Cbr /\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound shows a complex left ovarian mass with solid components and internal septations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dermoid cyst","Germ cell ovarian cancer","Fibroma","Epithelial ovarian cancer","Endometrioma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of ovarian cancer. The combination of persistent abdominal symptoms, post-menopausal status, significantly elevated CA-125, and complex ovarian mass on imaging is concerning for malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpithelial ovarian cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with vague symptoms such as bloating, early satiety, and pelvic discomfort. These symptoms are often present for several months before diagnosis. The presence of a fixed pelvic mass, elevated CA-125, and complex ultrasound features in a post-menopausal woman strongly suggests epithelial ovarian cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGerm cell ovarian cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in younger women (teens to early 20s) and often presents with rapid onset of symptoms. While it can cause elevated tumour markers, these are typically alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) or human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) rather than CA-125.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E (mature cystic teratoma) typically occurs in younger women and has characteristic ultrasound appearances including fat and calcification. It does not typically cause elevated CA-125 or constitutional symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a solid ovarian tumour that can occur in post-menopausal women but typically has normal CA-125 levels and does not cause systemic symptoms like weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrioma\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in a post-menopausal woman as it is estrogen-dependent. While it can cause elevated CA-125, it typically presents with cyclical pain and is uncommon after menopause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) is a useful tool that combines CA-125 level, menopausal status, and ultrasound features to assess the likelihood of malignancy in ovarian masses. This patient would score highly on the RMI and warrant urgent referral to a gynaecological oncologist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CA-125 is elevated in 80% of epithelial ovarian cancers but has poor specificity as it can be elevated in many benign conditions.","Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) combines CA-125, menopausal status, and ultrasound features to assess ovarian masses.","Post-menopausal women with persistent abdominal symptoms should be investigated for ovarian cancer."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). Ovarian Cysts in Postmenopausal Women: Green-top Guideline No. 34 [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2016. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-cysts-in-postmenopausal-women-green-top-guideline-no-34/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16677"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T16:24:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T16:24:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":